rket in art, Is He Dead? centers on a group of poor artists in Barbizon, France, who stage the death of a friend to drive up the price of his paintings. In order to make this scheme succeed, the artists hatch some hilarious plots involving cross-dressing, a full-scale fake funeral, lovers' deceptions, and much more. Mark Twain was fascinated by the theater and made many attempts at playwriting, but this play is certainly his best. Is He Dead? may have been too "out there" for the Victorian 1890s, but today's readers will thoroughly enjoy Mark Twain's well-crafted dialogue, intriguing cast of characters, and above all, his characteristic ebullience and humor. In Shelley Fisher Fishkin's estimation, it is "a champagne cocktail of a play--not too dry, not too sweet, with just the right amount of bubbles and buzz."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArtistsvDrama. 0aDeathvDrama. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican drama.  aamerican literature.  aamerican theater.  aart and literature.  aburlesque.  acomedy theater.  acomedy.  adeception.  afamous authors.  afarce.  aharebrained schemes.  ahumor.  ahumorists.  aillustrated.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary icons.  alive entertainment.  amanuscript.  amen and women.  amodern audiences.  aperforming arts.  aplaywrights.  asocial commentary.  asocial satire.  astage play.  atheatrical productions.  atwain scholars.  aworld market.1 aFishkin, Shelley Fisher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023979140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093989940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyte